05329nam a22008295i 9780812294484DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122944847 a10.9783/97808122944842doi  a(DE-B1597)491133  a(OCoLC)1015866555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1147.E85b.B874 2018 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a306.872309409022231 aBurger, Glenn D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConduct Becoming :bGood Wives and Husbands in the Later Middle Ages /cGlenn D. Burger. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b4 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Loving, Reading, Acting in a Marrying Kind of Way -- tChapter 1. Laboring to Make the Good Wife Good in the Journées Chrétiennes -- tChapter 2. Remaking the Feminine -- tChapter 3. In the Merchant’s Bedchamber: Le Menagier de Paris -- tChapter 4. Affecting Conduct: Feeling Steadfast with Griselda -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConduct Becoming examines a new genre of late medieval writing that focuses on a wife's virtuous conduct and ability of such conduct to alter marital and social relations in the world. Considering a range of texts written for women—the journées chrétiennes or daily guides for Christian living, secular counsel from husbands and fathers such as Le Livre du Chevalier de La Tour Landry and Le Menagier de Paris, and literary narratives such as the Griselda story—Glenn D. Burger argues that, over the course of the long fourteenth century, the "invention" of the good wife in discourses of sacramental marriage, private devotion, and personal conduct reconfigured how female embodiment was understood.While the period inherits a strongly antifeminist tradition that views the female body as naturally wayward and sensual, late medieval conduct texts for women outline models of feminine virtue that show the good wife as an identity with positive influence in the world. Because these manuals imagine how to be a good wife as necessarily entangled with how to be a good husband, they also move their readers to consider such gendered and sexed identities in relational terms and to embrace a model of self-restraint significantly different from that of clerical celibacy. Conduct literature addressed to the good wife thus reshapes how late medieval audiences thought about the process of becoming a good person more generally. Burger contends that these texts develop and promulgate a view of sex and gender radically different from previous clerical or aristocratic models—one capable of providing the foundations for the modern forms of heterosexuality that begin to emerge more clearly in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aConduct of life in literaturexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aMarriage in literaturexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSex rolezEuropexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSex rolezEuropexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aVirtue in literaturexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWives in literaturexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWivesxReligious lifezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWiveszEuropexConduct of lifexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomenxBooks and readingzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Co